WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.490 --> 00:00:08.280
&gt;&gt;Female presenter: Hi, everyone. Welcome
to AuthorsGoogle. I'm really excited to introduce

00:00:08.280 --> 00:00:14.280
Chris Guillebeau today. Chris is an author,
blogger, and all-around awesome human being.

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:20.030
He wrote the book, The Art of Nonconformity,
and has a really popular blog of the same

00:00:20.030 --> 00:00:27.330
name. Chris describes himself as a writer,
traveler, entrepreneur, and general nonconformist,

00:00:27.330 --> 00:00:32.520
and he's on a mission to visit every country
in the world before he turns 35. So, he's

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:40.480
currently visited about 151 countries, has
49 to go and is also running his book tour

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:48.710
in similar audacious fashion. He is visiting
all 50 states in a span of about two, two

00:00:48.710 --> 00:00:55.770
and a half months as well as ten Canadian
provinces. Chris's goals are to help people

00:00:55.770 --> 00:01:01.110
live unconventional lives, make their own
choices, and change the world. I know I've

00:01:01.110 --> 00:01:06.220
been personally very inspired by Chris and
his work, so without further ado, Chris Guillebeau.

00:01:06.220 --> 00:01:07.220
[applause]

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:15.430
&gt;&gt;Chris: Thanks so much. That was great. Thank
you so much. Thanks, Jenny that was wonderful.

00:01:15.430 --> 00:01:20.360
The one thing Jenny didn't mention is that
she's an author herself and her book is coming

00:01:20.360 --> 00:01:26.350
out, Life after College, in spring of next
year. So, I'm really excited about that. And

00:01:26.350 --> 00:01:30.670
thanks for your help in organizing this. Thanks,
Candice, for the posters, and thanks to all

00:01:30.670 --> 00:01:35.759
of you for being here. Thanks for welcoming
me to the Googleplex. So, I am psyched. It

00:01:35.759 --> 00:01:40.170
is an unconventional book tour, so because
of that, I don't wanna lecture for an hour.

00:01:40.170 --> 00:01:44.380
I'm sure you don't want that, either, and
I'm also going to assume that everyone here

00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:48.580
is literate. So, I won't read to you from
the book. If you want to read the book, you

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:55.039
can do so. That's great; if not, that's fine,
too. This is stop number 46 of the Unconventional

00:01:55.039 --> 00:01:59.420
Book Tour. It's been so much fun to go all
over the country and talk to fun people about

00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:05.219
nonconformity and unconventional life and
work of different forms. So, what I thought

00:02:05.219 --> 00:02:09.880
I'd do is I'll talk for about 15, 20 minutes.
I'll tell you a little bit about the book.

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:15.010
I'll tell you why I wrote it and what I hope
will come of it and a couple of things that

00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:19.170
are happening with the Art of Nonconformity
in general. And then we'll do what I call

00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:23.890
questions and attempted answers for about
15 minutes or so. So, sometimes that goes

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:27.170
better than others, but here, I'm sure, it's
gonna be great; at least we'll have great

00:02:27.170 --> 00:02:31.250
questions. And then we'll just hang out and
I'll be in the back after that to sign books

00:02:31.250 --> 00:02:35.280
for anybody who wants that. And normally,
I encourage people to bring cupcakes, but

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:39.350
here, at the Googleplex, that doesn't seem
to be an issue. So, again, we'll just hang

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:46.140
out and I'm so glad you're here. Quick audience
survey: How many of you have blogs of your

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:47.320
own?

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:52.650
[pause]
OK. And how many of you use Twitter? Awesome.

00:02:52.650 --> 00:03:00.650
OK, about a third with blogs, about 50% Twitter,
nice. So, the first question that often comes

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:09.070
up these days, why bother writing a book?
Like, what's the point? Because we live in

00:03:09.070 --> 00:03:16.790
this beautiful, digital age where we can get
information out to people immediately; we

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:22.410
can go tonight and write a blog post about
what happens here today. And no one's gonna

00:03:22.410 --> 00:03:27.620
tell us what to say. We have no editors, there's
no gatekeeper. And we can get that message

00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:32.850
out to tens of thousands or more people and
if we want instant feedback, we can get that

00:03:32.850 --> 00:03:38.640
with Twitter, Facebook, Side Comments, etc.
And I think it's all wonderful, but it also

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:45.130
begs the question, why bother writing a book?
Because a book is almost the opposite of that

00:03:45.130 --> 00:03:50.200
process. A book takes forever. The publishing
lifecycle takes a year or more. I wrote this

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:55.270
book last year; it just came out two months
ago. You have to give up control. There's

00:03:55.270 --> 00:04:00.060
no guarantee of success, etc. And so I was
thinking about this as I was going through

00:04:00.060 --> 00:04:06.470
the writing process and getting ready to publish
the book and I realized that, for me, I was

00:04:06.470 --> 00:04:10.180
always a big reader and I grew up reading
books and books were something that were very

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:18.310
special to me, and I could think of probably
five to ten books, at least, that I had read

00:04:18.310 --> 00:04:23.349
as a child or a teenager, as an adult, that
had really changed my life, that had really

00:04:23.349 --> 00:04:27.620
made a big impact or a big difference. And
after I read the book, I was a different person,

00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:32.710
or I made decisions differently. And I couldn't
really think of a lot of blog posts that have

00:04:32.710 --> 00:04:38.430
changed my life and I certainly couldn't think
of any tweets that changed my life; just reading

00:04:38.430 --> 00:04:41.979
through the tweet deck and like, "Wow. I'm
a different person." Couldn't think of anything

00:04:41.979 --> 00:04:48.439
like that. So, I think Twitter is great for
gathering people together and doing this Unconventional

00:04:48.439 --> 00:04:52.439
Book Tour and each stop along the way. Twitter,
Facebook, all those things have been fantastic

00:04:52.439 --> 00:04:57.099
in bringing people out. And I think it's also
good for making connections and sharing information

00:04:57.099 --> 00:05:04.129
and all kinds of things, but I also think
that a lot of digital communication is fleeting

00:05:04.129 --> 00:05:07.099
and a lot of it just goes out there and then
we move on to the next thing.

00:05:07.099 --> 00:05:08.099
[woman’s voice on intercom interference]

00:05:08.099 --> 00:05:14.819
All right. I guess we're gonna keep going.
Great.

00:05:14.819 --> 00:05:15.819
[laughter]

00:05:15.819 --> 00:05:19.969
So, a lot of communication goes out there
and if you have a blog of your own, you probably

00:05:19.969 --> 00:05:25.259
know that your archives are almost never read.
It's mostly only your current posts. Ninety

00:05:25.259 --> 00:05:30.509
percent of the traffic is going to your most
recent posts. And so, I guess I still believe

00:05:30.509 --> 00:05:35.219
that books, at least, have the potential to
be a little bit longer lasting, to make a

00:05:35.219 --> 00:05:40.249
little bit more of an impact, to be something
with a longer timeline, at least a different

00:05:40.249 --> 00:05:46.279
format. And it's not for me to say whether
this book will change anyone's life or not;

00:05:46.279 --> 00:05:50.770
that's for other people to judge. But I also
think it's good to have a goal and it's good

00:05:50.770 --> 00:05:56.270
to define your own success and if you're gonna
undertake a big project, you might as well

00:05:56.270 --> 00:06:00.650
decide for yourself what success is gonna
look like. And so, in my case with this book,

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:05.599
my hope with The Art of Nonconformity book
is that people will read it and say not only

00:06:05.599 --> 00:06:09.979
it was a good book, but hopefully say, "I
read this book and then I thought differently

00:06:09.979 --> 00:06:14.789
about some things and I went and made some
changes, or I made some different decisions."

00:06:14.789 --> 00:06:20.520
So, really, the goal is to inspire people
to take action, to create positive change,

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:26.310
or whatever positive change looks like in
their lives. And so, I like to frame the whole

00:06:26.310 --> 00:06:31.599
question around something that Gretchen Rubin
said. And Gretchen is the author of The Happiness

00:06:31.599 --> 00:06:36.389
Project book and blog and she's been a good
friend and mentor to me, and so on the first

00:06:36.389 --> 00:06:43.669
page of the book, Gretchen asks this question
and the question is, "In the face of relentless

00:06:43.669 --> 00:06:50.759
pressure to conform, and pressure to avoid
risks, how do we craft the life of our dreams?"

00:06:50.759 --> 00:06:54.960
Or another way to put it is, "How do we live
a remarkable life in a conventional world?"

00:06:54.960 --> 00:07:01.339
So, that's the central question of the book.
And I use this analogy in the prologue of

00:07:01.339 --> 00:07:05.920
jumping off a bridge, or bridge jumping. So,
bridge jumping comes from this experience

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:10.669
you might have had when you were a kid and
you wanted to do something that you probably

00:07:10.669 --> 00:07:15.960
shouldn't do and your parent or your teacher
or some authority figure said, "Jenny, why

00:07:15.960 --> 00:07:20.719
do you want to do that?" And she said, "Oh,
because Candice is doing it. Because Tim is

00:07:20.719 --> 00:07:25.819
doing it." And they said to her, "If everyone
else jumped off a bridge, would you?" So then

00:07:25.819 --> 00:07:30.289
she's a little bit disappointed, but she realizes,
hopefully, maybe it's good advice, which is

00:07:30.289 --> 00:07:37.650
all fine and well, but then we grow up and
the situation changes; kind of reverses itself.

00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:43.770
And we look around and we see that many of
our peers are making the same kind of decisions.

00:07:43.770 --> 00:07:48.330
And many of our peers are on one narrow path
and doing the same kind of things in terms

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:54.650
of their education, their career, their relationships,
how they think about money and debt and all

00:07:54.650 --> 00:08:01.029
kinds of things. And if we wanna do something
different, if we have an idea maybe to take

00:08:01.029 --> 00:08:06.059
the road not taken or even make our own road,
even if it's something that not confrontational,

00:08:06.059 --> 00:08:10.930
even if it's not opposed to someone else,
then we often encounter this resistance and

00:08:10.930 --> 00:08:14.979
we encounter this pressure to conform, that
Gretchen talked about, or this pressure to

00:08:14.979 --> 00:08:20.059
avoid risks. And so, it's almost like everyone's
asking us the opposite question. It's almost

00:08:20.059 --> 00:08:24.969
like everyone's saying, "Everyone else is
jumping off the bridge, why aren't you? What's

00:08:24.969 --> 00:08:31.509
wrong with you?" And so, the one sentence
statement of why I wrote the book is to bring

00:08:31.509 --> 00:08:36.800
the childhood message up to adulthood application
and to say, "You don't have to live your life

00:08:36.800 --> 00:08:41.930
the way other people expect you to and you
can do good things for yourself and for others

00:08:41.930 --> 00:08:48.660
at the same time." It's not a false choice,
it's not a dichotomy. And here are the stories

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:53.089
of a number of people who have done that in
different ways. So, I wrote the book, there's

00:08:53.089 --> 00:08:57.040
a number of stories about me and some people
will relate to those stories and others won't,

00:08:57.040 --> 00:09:01.570
and that's OK. But then there's stories of
other people who have somehow overcome the

00:09:01.570 --> 00:09:07.480
pressure to conform and pursued an unconventional
choice of their own. So for example, there's

00:09:07.480 --> 00:09:13.570
a story of Susan Lewis, who's from Dallas,
Texas, and Susan wanted to make a career change.

00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:17.880
She didn't actually want to be an entrepreneur;
she wanted to be part of a company or an organization

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:23.399
bigger than herself, but she realized any
job I apply for, there's probably gonna be

00:09:23.399 --> 00:09:28.540
a hundred other people, at least, applying
for this job. And maybe on paper they look

00:09:28.540 --> 00:09:35.240
as good as I do, so how can I get around this
situation? How can I circumvent the HR process?

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:40.660
And so, instead of sending out 300 emails
with her resume attached, in hopes that one

00:09:40.660 --> 00:09:47.000
company would call her back, Susan created
a website called "Susanhiresaboss.com" and

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:52.500
put her portfolio online and said, "Here's
who I am and here's what I've done, and most

00:09:52.500 --> 00:09:57.170
importantly, here's what I would like to do
for the right company or organization. And

00:09:57.170 --> 00:10:01.930
I am interviewing prospective bosses. If you'd
like to be considered, fill out this form."

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:06.899
So, of course that's very audacious, especially
at the height of the economic crisis, when

00:10:06.899 --> 00:10:11.750
unemployment was 12 to 14% in Texas, but Susan
did this and she got a lot of attention for

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:17.430
it and she got 12 to 14 good job offers from
companies all over North America. And the

00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:21.920
company that she ended up going to work for,
or the boss that she hired, to use her language,

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:26.769
was not actually planning on expanding their
organization until he heard about Susan's

00:10:26.769 --> 00:10:30.850
project and he was just really impressed with
her initiative and he said, "I have to make

00:10:30.850 --> 00:10:36.050
room in my organization for someone like Susan."
There's also a story about a guy named Alan

00:10:36.050 --> 00:10:43.540
Bacon and Alan was a self-described conventional
guy with a traditional job and a family, middle-aged,

00:10:43.540 --> 00:10:47.990
and Alan was happy with many parts of his
life, but he was also discontented and thinking

00:10:47.990 --> 00:10:54.259
about making some change, but he realized,
"I can't make a really big change. I can't

00:10:54.259 --> 00:10:57.660
just leave everything behind and move to Thailand,
like some people do. That's great that some

00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:03.190
people can do that, but I can't." So what
Alan did instead was, he created what he called

00:11:03.190 --> 00:11:09.940
a "series of life experiments." And the life
experiments began with really small things,

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:15.149
things like going to the art museum during
his lunch break. So, every day he drove to

00:11:15.149 --> 00:11:19.190
work and he passed this art museum and he
had never been inside. So one day, he went

00:11:19.190 --> 00:11:23.759
inside. And then he took up photography, which
was a hobby he had always been interested

00:11:23.759 --> 00:11:29.240
in, but had never really pursued. So he bought
a camera, took a class. Then he started doing

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:34.009
some travelling. He started doing some business
travel he hadn't done before. He went overseas

00:11:34.009 --> 00:11:38.019
to Europe for the first time and he found
out that he had to go back to France for about

00:11:38.019 --> 00:11:42.730
three weeks, and instead of going back by
himself, he found a way to bring his family

00:11:42.730 --> 00:11:48.350
with him. So, his wife and their three young
daughters went to France for a three week

00:11:48.350 --> 00:11:52.660
cross-cultural immersion experience; talked
about what a good decision that was for the

00:11:52.660 --> 00:11:57.389
family. And then Alan started consulting and
now he's completely self-employed. And he

00:11:57.389 --> 00:12:04.240
traces the whole process to the early idea
of the life experiments; to just being willing

00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:10.980
to experiment with change, to see change as
something welcoming instead of something fearful.

00:12:10.980 --> 00:12:17.259
So, the story of Susan, the story of Alan,
a number of other people in the book, again,

00:12:17.259 --> 00:12:22.490
with the goal of inspiring readers to take
action, to create positive change, to take

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:27.079
action to maybe step back from the bridge
and take a different look and see, "How can

00:12:27.079 --> 00:12:32.139
I pursue my own unconventional life?" And
so, when we talk about things like change,

00:12:32.139 --> 00:12:37.829
and we talk about nonconformity, unconventional
living, all these kinds of things, it’s

00:12:37.829 --> 00:12:42.410
good to mention that these are not things
that everyone cares about, and not everyone's

00:12:42.410 --> 00:12:47.470
interested in change and not everyone wants
to live unconventionally, and that's OK. So,

00:12:47.470 --> 00:12:51.709
I get a lot of emails and from time to time,
people will write in and say, "I have a very

00:12:51.709 --> 00:12:56.890
traditional life, what do you have against
me?" And it gives me a great opportunity to

00:12:56.890 --> 00:13:01.910
say I have nothing against you and I wish
you well and that's great, I'm so glad you're

00:13:01.910 --> 00:13:08.750
happy. The problem is that a lot of other
people are not happy with that and maybe not

00:13:08.750 --> 00:13:13.110
so much unhappy, but I would say a lot of
people are discontented and a lot of people

00:13:13.110 --> 00:13:18.550
are dissatisfied with the idea of doing things
the way they've always been done. And so,

00:13:18.550 --> 00:13:22.310
in many ways, the fundamental message of The
Art of Nonconformity, the whole project, is

00:13:22.310 --> 00:13:27.769
really for the discontented. It's a self-selecting
group of people who do want to do something

00:13:27.769 --> 00:13:33.180
different. And for those of us who find ourselves
in that group, for people who identify with

00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:39.040
that and say, "Yes, I do want to pursue the
road not taken, or make my own road," I've

00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:44.170
been doing these meet-ups all across the country.
San Francisco is number 46 and out of all

00:13:44.170 --> 00:13:49.329
these conversations, I've developed just two
suggestions. So, two suggestions for those

00:13:49.329 --> 00:13:56.779
of us who find ourselves in that group. The
first suggestion is that these days, there

00:13:56.779 --> 00:14:02.459
is a lot of conversation about efficiency,
about how to be the most efficient person

00:14:02.459 --> 00:14:07.200
or the most productive, or how to live the
most optimal life; how to get up at 5 o'clock

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:13.000
in the morning and read your 60 RSS feeds
by 6 AM, or how to outsource your life and

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:17.990
get other people to do things for you, so
that you can detach yourself from humanity.

00:14:17.990 --> 00:14:23.600
And I think that's a little bit overrated.
And my response to that would be the same

00:14:23.600 --> 00:14:27.209
as with the other people. I would say, "If
that works for you; that's great, if that

00:14:27.209 --> 00:14:31.879
rocks your world, wonderful." But for those
of us who might be a little bit uncomfortable

00:14:31.879 --> 00:14:36.500
with that, or for those of us who might wonder,
"Is that it? Is that the answer?" I would

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:43.329
say that there's an alternative, and the alternative
to pursuing efficiency for efficiency's sake,

00:14:43.329 --> 00:14:50.260
is to pursue meaningful adventure. So, things
like, in my case, visiting every country in

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:54.579
the world. For those of you who read the blog,
you know it's a highly inefficient quest.

00:14:54.579 --> 00:15:01.139
I spend a lot of time and money and energy
sorting out plane tickets and logistics and

00:15:01.139 --> 00:15:05.540
Visas and sleeping on the floor of the airport
all over the world, and getting kicked out

00:15:05.540 --> 00:15:11.589
of various countries. And it's all very inefficient
and in many ways, my life could be much easier

00:15:11.589 --> 00:15:15.639
if I just didn't do that; if I just lived
at home in Portland, Oregon, maybe travelled

00:15:15.639 --> 00:15:19.769
around the States, maybe traveled once a year.
But I don't do it because it’s efficient

00:15:19.769 --> 00:15:24.220
or productive; I do it because it’s meaningful.
It brings personal joy to me; that's why I

00:15:24.220 --> 00:15:30.819
do it. Another example would be this book
tour itself. About 90 days before the book

00:15:30.819 --> 00:15:35.319
came out, I talked to my publisher and I said,
"Hey guys. What's the plan for the book tour?

00:15:35.319 --> 00:15:40.300
Where am I going?" And they said, "Oh, we
don't have any money for that and we don't

00:15:40.300 --> 00:15:43.949
really believe in book tours anymore. Most
authors don't really want to do them anyway."

00:15:43.949 --> 00:15:48.779
And they said, "You can come to New York if
you want." And I said, "Well, New York is

00:15:48.779 --> 00:15:54.319
great, but not everyone lives there." So,
I just decided if there's no official book

00:15:54.319 --> 00:16:00.380
tour, well that's OK. I'll make my own. And
I don't want to do anything small, so I don't

00:16:00.380 --> 00:16:03.900
want to only do major markets. So, that's
how the whole 50 state thing came about and

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:07.870
I didn't want to leave out Canada, so all
the provinces up there. And I just figured

00:16:07.870 --> 00:16:11.990
it’s not only me, it's all of my great readers.
I have great readers all over the country

00:16:11.990 --> 00:16:16.160
and we'll just make this happen and we'll
find a way to do it, however we can do it.

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:21.970
And it's been so fantastic. It's been so much
fun, so rewarding, so meaningful and it's

00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:25.389
great that I can go to places and have great
crowds. It's great that I can come here to

00:16:25.389 --> 00:16:29.949
Google, but some of the smaller stops, in
many ways, have actually been more meaningful;

00:16:29.949 --> 00:16:35.439
to go to a place like North Dakota where there's
nine people, until a few days before. I went

00:16:35.439 --> 00:16:39.829
to West Virginia and there was only one person
on the sign-up list and her name was Nancy.

00:16:39.829 --> 00:16:44.009
So I wrote to her and said, "Nancy, you have
to be there. You can't get sick, you can't

00:16:44.009 --> 00:16:46.580
skip it, because it's you and me and West
Virginia."

00:16:46.580 --> 00:16:47.999
[laughter]

00:16:47.999 --> 00:16:52.480
So it's one of those things that doesn't make
sense from an economic perspective, or from

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:58.600
a marketing perspective. But again, it's an
adventure. It's fun. So, instead of efficiency,

00:16:58.600 --> 00:17:05.949
consider meaningful adventure. And the second
of just two suggestions comes from the awareness

00:17:05.949 --> 00:17:10.280
that these are really privileged conversations
that we're able to have. And I think it's

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:15.559
fantastic that we can talk about things like
what kind of work we would like to do and

00:17:15.559 --> 00:17:20.659
how we would like to spend our time and what
blogs we read. And so, it's great, but it's

00:17:20.659 --> 00:17:25.079
also very unusual; it's very remarkable and
it's very privileged to be able to talk about

00:17:25.079 --> 00:17:29.679
these things. And so, something that I think
is missing from the whole conversation about

00:17:29.679 --> 00:17:35.520
alternative life and work, is this question
of contribution; the question, "What can we

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:40.150
contribute?" instead of just, "What can we
consume?" or "How can we engage instead of

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:44.250
detach?" And so, that's why I say that the
two most important questions in the universe

00:17:44.250 --> 00:17:49.080
are, number one, what do you really want to
get out of life? Because a lot of people don't

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:53.490
know what they want, so I think if they can
figure that out, that's great. But then, number

00:17:53.490 --> 00:17:59.279
two, what can you offer the world that no
one else can? So that's that question of contribution,

00:17:59.279 --> 00:18:03.971
a question of engagement. And it's good to
say, when we talked about contribution, and

00:18:03.971 --> 00:18:09.470
it's not entirely a selfless act, it's not
a sacrificial thing, at least not entirely,

00:18:09.470 --> 00:18:14.770
because we ourselves benefit as we contribute,
and we, ourselves, are made better as we seek

00:18:14.770 --> 00:18:21.260
to answer that question of contribution. So,
it's good for everyone. And my story is, after

00:18:21.260 --> 00:18:27.039
9/11, I was depressed like everyone else and
just asking myself the big questions of life

00:18:27.039 --> 00:18:32.600
and my wife and I are talking about what can
we do and is there a way we can respond? How

00:18:32.600 --> 00:18:36.440
can we do something to give back? And it was
out of that situation that we ended up moving

00:18:36.440 --> 00:18:41.440
to West Africa and living in Sierra Leone
and Liberia for about four years, volunteering

00:18:41.440 --> 00:18:46.350
for a medical charity. And it was just the
most amazing, transformative experience of

00:18:46.350 --> 00:18:50.460
our lives. It was very good for us and we
would come back to the States about every

00:18:50.460 --> 00:18:54.760
year or so, and we would talk with people
about what we were doing, and people would

00:18:54.760 --> 00:18:59.700
say things like, "Oh, that's amazing. How
sacrificial of you." And we realized pretty

00:18:59.700 --> 00:19:04.590
quickly to become uncomfortable with that
kind of dialogue because we would say, Oh,

00:19:04.590 --> 00:19:09.310
it is great that we can do this and it is
wonderful that we can be a part of something

00:19:09.310 --> 00:19:15.240
bigger than ourselves and that we can help
an organization that's working in post-conflict

00:19:15.240 --> 00:19:19.390
countries, and that's good. And people's lives
are being made better through that, but it's

00:19:19.390 --> 00:19:22.980
not the whole story. The whole story is that
our lives are being made better through this,

00:19:22.980 --> 00:19:27.190
also. And we are also being changed. So really
this is the best decision that we've ever

00:19:27.190 --> 00:19:34.620
made. And so, that's why I call it a selfish
generosity as we seek to answer that question

00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:38.779
of contribution and we, ourselves, are made
better. So, when you put all these things

00:19:38.779 --> 00:19:45.610
together, along with this opportunity to embrace
life as a meaningful adventure, instead of

00:19:45.610 --> 00:19:51.740
something to be lived to its most efficient
state all the time, along with the imperative

00:19:51.740 --> 00:19:55.770
to really think about contribution and think
about what we can give and how we can engage.

00:19:55.770 --> 00:20:02.429
I think what it all comes down to is a question
of legacy, of what will our legacy be? And

00:20:02.429 --> 00:20:06.000
what are we building and what kind of story
do we hope to tell with our lives and what

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:12.210
will the ultimate impact of our lives be?
And I think of legacy as having nothing to

00:20:12.210 --> 00:20:17.970
do with money, nothing to do with inheritance,
even career. It's certainly nothing that we

00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:22.950
think about at the end of our lives, looking
back, when we can't really make any changes,

00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:28.350
but rather, legacy is something to think about
from whatever stage in our life we're in.

00:20:28.350 --> 00:20:33.950
And I think it's a question of influence and
relationships and that part of contribution

00:20:33.950 --> 00:20:38.070
that I talked about. And so, that's what I've
been trying to do with The Art of Nonconformity,

00:20:38.070 --> 00:20:42.940
with the blog, and now the book, the business,
the whole community. I like to be very clear

00:20:42.940 --> 00:20:47.540
that it's been a work in progress from the
beginning and it continues to be. I wasn't

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:51.270
really clear about the project in the beginning
and that's normally how it goes. I began with

00:20:51.270 --> 00:20:56.740
a classic blogging strategy of making shit
up. I'm sure no one at Google is familiar

00:20:56.740 --> 00:21:02.490
