&gt;&gt;Chris: Thanks, man.

00:34:21.990 --> 00:34:29.149
&gt;&gt;Male audience #4: Let me start with this
one. What sort of mental techniques do you

00:34:29.149 --> 00:34:39.890
use to try to quelch risk-aversion? So, if
you're going on a trip around the world and

00:34:39.890 --> 00:34:45.790
you've got this stuff in your backpack and
this amount of money in the bank, there's

00:34:45.790 --> 00:34:53.240
certainly scenarios that you could get yourself
in trouble. So, you or other people that you've

00:34:53.240 --> 00:34:58.400
read, what sort of techniques do you use to
say, "I'm really ready to do this, I'm as

00:34:58.400 --> 00:35:00.380
safe as I can be. Let's just go for it."

00:35:00.380 --> 00:35:02.230
&gt;&gt;Chris: That's a great question. What was
your name?

00:35:02.230 --> 00:35:03.230
&gt;&gt;audience #4: Jeremy.

00:35:03.230 --> 00:35:07.220
&gt;&gt;Chris: Jeremy thanks. That was awesome.
I don't know if I have any mental techniques,

00:35:07.220 --> 00:35:14.780
but I guess what I try to do and what I encourage
people to do is think about risk differently,

00:35:14.780 --> 00:35:21.700
and maybe redefine risk a little bit. So,
the example of travel; this comes up a lot.

00:35:21.700 --> 00:35:27.290
People always ask me about dangerous countries
and bad things that have happened and aren't

00:35:27.290 --> 00:35:31.950
you scared, etc. And I always point out that
there are some dangerous countries in the

00:35:31.950 --> 00:35:37.140
world, yes. But the list is very, very small.
Basically, like five to ten countries in the

00:35:37.140 --> 00:35:42.470
world that actually could be called dangerous
and there's 180 countries which are totally

00:35:42.470 --> 00:35:47.750
fine. So, I also say the more you do something,
then the more comfortable you become. When

00:35:47.750 --> 00:35:52.510
the risk comes about, or the feeling of risk,
the fear, usually comes about when we haven't

00:35:52.510 --> 00:35:56.630
done something and we're thinking about doing
something, but we don't know what it’s like.

00:35:56.630 --> 00:36:01.790
Once we get the experience, we look back and
say, "Oh, maybe not so much." The other thing

00:36:01.790 --> 00:36:10.819
I would say about risk is, in terms of entrepreneurships,
small business, working for companies; traditionally

00:36:10.819 --> 00:36:16.610
security has been defined as working for a
company. And entrepreneurship is seen as the

00:36:16.610 --> 00:36:21.180
risky alternative and entrepreneurs take risks.
Therefore, they are rewarded for their risk,

00:36:21.180 --> 00:36:27.550
or they might fail. And I think a lot of what's
happened over the past few years has redefined

00:36:27.550 --> 00:36:30.970
that. And I think a lot of beliefs have been
questioned. We used to have the belief that

00:36:30.970 --> 00:36:34.340
the stock market is always going to go up.
We used to have the belief that homeownership

00:36:34.340 --> 00:36:39.240
is the best choice for everyone. And, I think,
more and more people are looking at that and

00:36:39.240 --> 00:36:45.330
saying, "What is risk? And what is security?"
In my case, I think it would be risky for

00:36:45.330 --> 00:36:50.630
me to have a job. I think working for myself
is the less risky, I think it’s the safe,

00:36:50.630 --> 00:36:56.619
conservative choice. So, people often talk
about risk in the sense of starting a business,

00:36:56.619 --> 00:37:01.850
but it can actually be a very safe choice.
So, I like to think about risk and think about

00:37:01.850 --> 00:37:03.960
what the real risk is and maybe redefine it.

